Patient has a history of type 2 diabetes for approximately 10 years. Patient had taken Metformin in the past, but stopped taking when he lost insurance. Patient reports polyuria/polydipsia for the last 2 weeks. Also reports blurry vision for 3 to 4 days prior to admission and a 10 pound weight loss over the last 2 weeks. Patient had been on a course of prednisone 60 mg daily from 2/2021-12-15 for treatment of TTP. However, noted that patient's blood glucose has ranged from 157-318 for the last 4 months, with his last documented blood glucose being 318 on 2022-11-25, prior to starting steroids. Patient's blood glucose was 767 on admission yesterday, with an anion gap of 16 and trace ketones. Patient also noted to be in renal failure, with EGFR 29. Noted that patient's eGFR had ranged from 37-46 for the 4 months prior to admission. Patient was initially on insulin drip, then transitioned to Lantus 10 units and medium dose sliding scale last night. Patient received an additional 20 units of Lantus this afternoon, with subsequent dosing scheduled every morning. Patient is taking 60 g CHO diet fairly well, but also eating a lot of fruit brought in from home.

Patient is 53 y/o male with a pmhx significant for CAD s/p CABG, HTN, DM, CKD, CHF and peripheral vascular disease, AAA s/p repair, and CA stenosis s/p stent placement, who presents to the ED from Brown Cancer center due abnormal labs. Pt had an appointment with his hematologist, Dr. Cisak, at the Brown Cancer Center today where routine labs showed that he had a glucose of 767 and Na of 116 (corrected Na of 127), K 5.6, Cl 80, bicarb 20, AG 16, glu 767, BUN 59, Cr 2.84, normal AST/ALT. He was sent to the ED for management of his hyperglycemia. Pt reports that he started having itching in groin area x 2 days, with headaches with blurry vision. He endorses increased thirst and urination, numbness/tingling in his lower extremities and weight loss in the past month. Pt denies fever, chills, SOB, chest pain, HA, N/V. Pt was started on Prednisone 60mg daily on 2022-12-15 for his thrombocytopenia secondary to ITP. He reports that he was diagnosed with low plts 2021 when he was undergoing surgery for his AAA and carotid artery stenosis. He denies any spontaneous bleeding. He has not been on any diabetes medications for several years. He denies any acute symptoms currently except for tingling/ pain in his feet bilaterally.
In the ED, pt was afebrile with VS. Labs showed CBC with diff: WBC 11.6, hgb 14, hct 41.5, plt 51. CMP showed Na 121 (corrected 130), K 4.5, Cl 84, bicarb 20, AG 17, glu 664, BUN 595 Cr 2.7, normal AST/ALT. His ABG shows no acidosis. UA showed >1000 glu but no ketones. Repeat BG level was >500. x 2 Pt was given calcium gluconate for cardiac protection, 10 units of insulin, NS bolus 1L x 1 and started on an insulin drip. Family medicine was called to evaluate the patient and admit fro HHS.
Upon my evaluation, pt is is no distress. Endorses pain/ tingling in feet b/l, otherwise feels fine.

HHS secondary to uncontrolled diabetes and steroid use, resolved
Hx of diabetes, not on diabetic regimen, used to take metformin "several years" ago. Recently started taking steroids for thrombocytopenia and completed course between 2022-12-15 until 2022-12-22. He was given insulin 10 units x 1 in the ED and was started on an insulin drip. His BG corrected and his anion gap closed. Insulin drip was stopped and he was transitioned to subcutaneous insulin. He was started on a basal bolus regimen of Lantus 20 units and admelog 6 units TID with meals with medium sliding scale insulin at meals. Diabetes nurse practitioner was consulted who recommended the following:
Start Admelog 6 units 3 times daily with meals. Continue Lantus 20 units every morning and medium dose sliding scale. However, anticipate decrease in insulin requirements within the next day or two due to renal insufficiency. Given patient's renal insufficiency will discharge on approximately 0.3 units/kg/day total insulin, given as Lantus 10 units every morning and Humalog 4 units 3 times daily with meals. Prescriptions for diabetes medications and supplies have been sent to his preferred pharmacy. Once patient's blood glucose has normalized and his beta cell toxicity has sufficiently resolved, he may be a candidate for Lantus plus Trulicity after outpatient follow-up. Home blood glucose goal of 100-150 prior to meals for now. Also advised patient that he will likely need frequent insulin dose adjustment, as his renal function may vary.
Education was provided prior to discharge and medications were sent to patient's preferred pharmacy at discharge. Pt was advised to follow up with PCP in 2-3 days for management.
Thrombocytopenia
Diagnosed in 2022-05-17- range 37,000-61,0000/ul, however pt has not had any spontaneous bleeding in the past . Has been following up with Hematology who believed that it is secondary to TTP vs liver disease. His platelets decreased from 51 to 46 on 2022-12-25. Antiplatelet regimen was held (ASA and clopidogrel) due to plt count <50. He did not have any spontaneous bleeding during admission and remained hemodynamically stable. Steroids were held. Hematology recommended restarting antiplatelet therapy/ anticoagulation (ASA/clopidogrel) once plt stabilize to >50,000. Plts at discharge were 25, however, pt did not have any spontaneous/ active bleeding. Hematology recommended no platelet transfusion and recommended follow up with their office within 1 week after discharge to recheck labs.
Uncontrolled DM
Not on any diabetes medications at home. A1c was 15.4 in the hospital. After his HHS resolved, he was started on Lantus 20 units at bedtime with Admelog 6 units TID with meals with medium SSI. Diabetes NP was consulted who gave recommendations as above. Pt was given education about how to use medications and check BG levels at home. Pt instructed to FU with PCP within 2-3 days after discharge.
Hypotension
Pt's BP was <100 systolic, however, pt remained asymptomatic. His home medications (Entresto, metoprolol, spironolactone) were held during hospitalization and at discharge. Recommended follow up with PCP for blood pressure check and to restart medications.
CHF
Did not appear fluid overload on exam while in the hospital. His BNP was 133. He was hypotensive during his hospital stay. His home regimen (metoprolol 75 mg BID, spironolactone 12.5 mg daily, Entresto 24-26 mg BID) was held. He was given IV fluids and also normal saline boluses, however, was still hypotensive, without symptoms. He was recommended to FU with PCP for restarting medications.

Hyperglycemia
Hyperglycemia is when the sugar (glucose) level in your blood is too high. It may not cause symptoms. If you do have symptoms, they may include warning signs, such as:
• Feeling more thirsty than normal.
• Hunger.
• Feeling tired.
• Needing to pee (urinate) more than normal.
• Blurry eyesight (vision).
You may get other symptoms as it gets worse, such as:
• Dry mouth.
• Not being hungry (loss of appetite).
• Fruity-smelling breath.
• Weakness.
• Weight gain or loss that is not planned. Weight loss may be fast.
• A tingling or numb feeling in your hands or feet.
• Headache.
• Skin that does not bounce back quickly when it is lightly pinched and released (poor skin turgor).
• Pain in your belly (abdomen).
• Cuts or bruises that heal slowly.
High blood sugar can happen to people who do or do not have diabetes. High blood sugar can happen slowly or quickly, and it can be an emergency.
Follow these instructions at home:
General instructions
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor.
• Do not use products that contain nicotine or tobacco, such as cigarettes and e-cigarettes. If you need help quitting, ask your doctor.
• Limit alcohol intake to no more than 1 drink per day for nonpregnant women and 2 drinks per day for men. One drink equals 12 oz of beer, 5 oz of wine, or 1½ oz of hard liquor.
• Manage stress. If you need help with this, ask your doctor.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
Eating and drinking
• Stay at a healthy weight.
• Exercise regularly, as told by your doctor.
• Drink enough fluid, especially when you:
◦ Exercise.
◦ Get sick.
◦ Are in hot temperatures.
• Eat healthy foods, such as:
◦ Low-fat (lean) proteins.
◦ Complex carbs (complex carbohydrates), such as whole wheat bread or brown rice.
◦ Fresh fruits and vegetables.
◦ Low-fat dairy products.
◦ Healthy fats.
• Drink enough fluid to keep your pee (urine) clear or pale yellow.
If you have diabetes:
• Make sure you know the symptoms of hyperglycemia.
• Follow your diabetes management plan, as told by your doctor. Make sure you:
◦ Take insulin and medicines as told.
◦ Follow your exercise plan.
◦ Follow your meal plan. Eat on time. Do not skip meals.
◦ Check your blood sugar as often as told. Make sure to check before and after exercise. If you exercise longer or in a different way than you normally do, check your blood sugar more often.
◦ Follow your sick day plan whenever you cannot eat or drink normally. Make this plan ahead of time with your doctor.
• Share your diabetes management plan with people in your workplace, school, and household.
• Check your urine for ketones when you are ill and as told by your doctor.
• Carry a card or wear jewelry that says that you have diabetes.
Contact a doctor if:
• Your blood sugar level is higher than 240 mg/dL (13.3 mmol/L) for 2 days in a row.
• You have problems keeping your blood sugar in your target range.
• High blood sugar happens often for you.
Get help right away if:
• You have trouble breathing.
• You have a change in how you think, feel, or act (mental status).
• You feel sick to your stomach (nauseous), and that feeling does not go away.
• You cannot stop throwing up (vomiting).
These symptoms may be an emergency. Do not wait to see if the symptoms will go away. Get medical help right away. Call your local emergency services (911 in the U.S.). Do not drive yourself to the hospital.
Summary
• Hyperglycemia is when the sugar (glucose) level in your blood is too high.
• High blood sugar can happen to people who do or do not have diabetes.
• Make sure you drink enough fluids, eat healthy foods, and exercise regularly.
• Contact your doctor if you have problems keeping your blood sugar in your target range.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
